"Jorquera-Fontena E., Orrego-Verdugo R.","Impact of global warming on the phenology of a variety of grapevine grown in southern Chile [Impacto del calentamiento global en la fenología de una variedad de vid cultivada en el sur de Chile]",2010,"Agrociencia","44","4",,"427","435",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77956431876&partnerID=40&md5=cbfd39ad6a822394f543df4f3e4be196","Facultad de Ingeniería, Ciencias y Administración, Universidad de la Frontera, Temuco, Chile; Avenida Francisco Salazar, 01145, Casilla 54-D, Chile","Jorquera-Fontena, E., Facultad de Ingeniería, Ciencias y Administración, Universidad de la Frontera, Temuco, Chile, Avenida Francisco Salazar, 01145, Casilla 54-D, Chile; Orrego-Verdugo, R., Facultad de Ingeniería, Ciencias y Administración, Universidad de la Frontera, Temuco, Chile, Avenida Francisco Salazar, 01145, Casilla 54-D, Chile","The trend to increased temperatures would lead to great changes in the development cycle of plants and style of agriculture in a particular locality. The effect of the temperatures projected by the IPCC on the phenology of Vitis vinifera (L.) Gewurtztraminer variety, in two areas of cold climate viticulture in southern Chile, was analyzed in this paper. A mathematical model was adjusted on phenology data and degree-days collected for two years. The model obtained was run with temperature data from current weather and those projected with the A2 and B2 scenarios for the period 2070-2100. The analysis of the results shows that local climate would present significant increases in the temperature sums (degree-days), reducing up to 17 d the bud-burst to flowering period and between 28-46 d the period of sprouting to harvest, in the most extreme scenario. Phenology is very sensitive to global warming scenarios and probable climate change. Characterizing its possible behavior could serve as reference to define strategies for the future planning of a vineyard.","Degree-days; Model; Temperature","Vitaceae; Vitis; Vitis vinifera",,,,,,"Amerine, M.A., Winkler, A.J., Composition and quality of musts and wines of California grapes (1974) Hilgardia, 5, pp. 493-675; Bindi, M., Fibbi, L., Gozzini, B., Orlandini, S., Miglietta, F., Modelling the impact of future climate scenarios on yield and yield variability of grapevine (1996) Climate Res., 7, pp. 213-224; Baron, C., Sultan, B., Balme, M., Sarr, B., Traore, S., Level, T., Janicot, S., Dingkuhn, M., From GCM grid cell to agricultural plot: Scale issues affecting model of climate impact (2005) Philosophal Trans. Royal Soc. B., 360, pp. 2095-2108; Bodwen, P., Edwars, C., Ocean Circulation/Surface Wind-Driven Circulation (2003) Encyclopedia of Atmospheric Science, pp. 1540-1549. , Holton, J., J. Curry, and J. Pyle (eds). Elsevier, U.K; Campbell, G.S., (1990) ClimGen, climatic data generador, , http://www.bsuse.wsu.edu/climgen, Washington State University. (consultado 29 abril 2009); Challinor, A.J., Ewert, F., Arnold, S., Simelton, E., Fraser, E., Crops and climate change: Progress, trends, and challenges in simulating impacts and informing adaptation (2009) J. Exp. Bot., 60 (10), pp. 2775-2789; Fuenzalida, H., Falvey, M., Rojas, M., Aceituno, P., Garreaud, R., Estudio de la variabilidad climática en Chile para el siglo XXI (2006) Informe para CONAMA, p. 71; Gordon, C., Cooper, C., Senior, C., Banks, H., Gregory, J., Johns, T., Mitchell, J., Word, R., The simulation of SST, sea ice extents and ocean heat transports in a version of the Hadley Centre coupled model without Flux adjustments (2000) Climate Dynamics, 16, pp. 147-168; Climate Change 2001: The scientific basis (2001) Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the IPCC, p. 882. , IPCC (Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change), Working Goup I. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK; Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis (2007) Contribution of Working Group I to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Clima